WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:03.820
Thank you. Thank everyone who come here for

2
00:00:03.880 --> 00:00:05.560
this panel. So this panel is

3
00:00:07.100 --> 00:00:11.060
really focusing on GLP-1s. We're going to talk about from mechanisms to

4
00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:12.100
real evidence.

5
00:00:13.880 --> 00:00:14.200
For that,

6
00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:16.000
if I can remember,

7
00:00:18.500 --> 00:00:22.180
the emerging role of GLP-1 in cancer prevention and outcomes.

8
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.520
We have three speakers. I'm Zhong Bian from Indiana University.

9
00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:29.820
I'm going to chair the session. And then we have two wonderful

10
00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:30.680
panelists.

11
00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:32.759
The first

12
00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:36.100
talk you're going to hear is from Dr.

13
00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:36.880
Jennifer

14
00:00:37.780 --> 00:00:41.220
Ligibel from Dana-Farber Cancer Institute at Harvard, and she's going to

15
00:00:41.880 --> 00:00:45.840
talk about obesity and cancer, kind of the general theme, whether it's a

16
00:00:45.880 --> 00:00:47.840
modifiable risk factor or not. And

17
00:00:48.980 --> 00:00:50.550
then it's going to be followed by Dr.

18
00:00:51.020 --> 00:00:52.820
Steve Hursting from

19
00:00:54.500 --> 00:00:58.000
Lineberger Comprehensive Cancer Center at UNC, and

20
00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:01.820
he's going to dig into more of the preclinical evidence

21
00:01:02.800 --> 00:01:06.140
for the anti-cancer effects and the mechanism of GLP-1.

22
00:01:06.840 --> 00:01:10.600
And I'm going to follow at the end, really just talk about some of the real-world

23
00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:12.280
evidence on GLP-1

24
00:01:13.240 --> 00:01:17.080
on cancer, both risk and outcomes, and some of the open questioning from

25
00:01:17.140 --> 00:01:20.240
our studies. So let's welcome the first speaker, Dr.

26
00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:22.080
Jennifer Ligibel.

27
00:01:31.780 --> 00:01:35.240
Thank you all, and good morning. It's great to be here.

28
00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:38.570
Thanks to the conference organizers for inviting me to kick off this

29
00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:42.000
session on GLP-1s and cancer.

30
00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:46.550
I'm going to talk a bit about obesity and whether this

31
00:01:46.620 --> 00:01:50.520
is truly a modifiable risk factor for the development of cancer

32
00:01:51.140 --> 00:01:54.440
or for cancer control after cancer is diagnosed.

33
00:01:55.940 --> 00:01:56.560
Let's see here.

34
00:01:58.220 --> 00:02:01.670
There we go. So we're going to start by reviewing some of the observational

35
00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:05.410
evidence. Why are we even having a session today talking about weight loss

36
00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:08.720
drugs and cancer? And then review the evidence that we

37
00:02:08.801 --> 00:02:12.549
have looking at other strategies to manage weight,

38
00:02:12.680 --> 00:02:16.280
lifestyle-based weight loss, bariatric surgery, and what we

39
00:02:16.340 --> 00:02:20.130
know about these types of interventions and their potential

40
00:02:20.180 --> 00:02:23.620
impact on an individual's risk of developing cancer

41
00:02:24.140 --> 00:02:28.060
or their risk of dying from malignancy once cancer has been diagnosed.

42
00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:33.440
So why obesity and cancer? We've known for a long

43
00:02:33.560 --> 00:02:37.460
time that excess adiposity increases an

44
00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:40.000
individual's risk of developing cancer.

45
00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:42.370
It's been now more than a decade since Dr.

46
00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:46.530
Hursting and I were part of this International Agency for Research in

47
00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:50.620
Cancer effort to really summarize all of these data

48
00:02:50.660 --> 00:02:54.030
looking at the relationship between excess adiposity,

49
00:02:54.530 --> 00:02:57.920
whether measured by body mass index or body composition,

50
00:02:58.040 --> 00:03:01.760
waist-hip ratio, and the risk of developing cancer.

51
00:03:02.380 --> 00:03:06.140
Over the course of about 10 days, we reviewed more than 1,000 studies

52
00:03:06.260 --> 00:03:09.920
looking at these relationships and found that there were more than a

53
00:03:09.940 --> 00:03:13.380
dozen malignancies for which there was clear and consistent

54
00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:17.240
evidence that as adiposity increased, so did the

55
00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:19.220
risk of developing that malignancy.

56
00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:22.280
And you can see from this list that there's a number of very common

57
00:03:22.400 --> 00:03:26.340
cancers that are part of this obesity-cancer connection,

58
00:03:26.420 --> 00:03:30.120
things like breast cancer and colon cancer, ovarian cancer.

59
00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:35.180
As an oncologist, I focus specifically on breast cancer, and I'm going to talk a

60
00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:39.109
bit about breast cancer throughout this session this morning because

61
00:03:39.140 --> 00:03:43.040
this is really the place where a lot of these relationships between

62
00:03:43.100 --> 00:03:46.710
obesity and cancer risk and outcomes really started.

63
00:03:47.300 --> 00:03:50.590
And when thinking about breast cancer in particular, this

64
00:03:50.590 --> 00:03:54.370
analysis through the International Agency for Research in Cancer found

65
00:03:54.400 --> 00:03:58.380
that every five kilogram per meter squared increase

66
00:03:58.420 --> 00:04:02.220
in body mass index, which is what takes somebody from normal weight

67
00:04:02.280 --> 00:04:06.109
into overweight, overweight into obesity, each of those was

68
00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:10.120
associated with a 10% increase in a woman's risk of

69
00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:12.660
developing breast cancer after menopause.

70
00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:16.680
So if you look at somebody of normal body weight, as you have increasing

71
00:04:16.721 --> 00:04:20.640
levels of obesity, this starts to be a very important risk factor for

72
00:04:20.680 --> 00:04:22.220
the development of breast cancer.

73
00:04:23.900 --> 00:04:27.700
We also know that obesity continues to be very important even

74
00:04:27.800 --> 00:04:31.680
after cancer has been diagnosed. This analysis

75
00:04:31.760 --> 00:04:34.640
looked at the relationship between body mass

76
00:04:34.760 --> 00:04:38.010
index and cancer outcomes in more than

77
00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:42.100
six million individuals diagnosed with either an

78
00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:45.010
early-stage or a later-stage malignancy.

79
00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:49.620
In this analysis, the investigators found that across

80
00:04:49.720 --> 00:04:53.360
all cancers, individuals with obesity had a

81
00:04:53.400 --> 00:04:57.070
higher risk of all-cause mortality, had a higher

82
00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:01.140
risk of cancer-specific mortality, and had a higher

83
00:05:01.260 --> 00:05:05.180
risk of cancer recurrence compared to individuals diagnosed with

84
00:05:05.240 --> 00:05:08.880
the same malignancies whose body mass index was in the normal

85
00:05:08.900 --> 00:05:09.440
range.

86
00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:14.180
Now, we know that obesity impacts some cancers more than others.

87
00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:18.080
So the group then looked at the relationship between

88
00:05:18.140 --> 00:05:21.580
obesity at the time of cancer diagnosis and

89
00:05:21.640 --> 00:05:25.620
cancer-specific mortality across different malignancies.

90
00:05:26.350 --> 00:05:30.200
They found, not surprisingly, that some of the strongest evidence that

91
00:05:30.280 --> 00:05:34.020
increased adiposity, obesity at diagnosis was

92
00:05:34.060 --> 00:05:37.120
associated with poor outcomes was seen in breast cancer.

93
00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:41.000
And you can see that across 36 studies, obesity

94
00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:44.760
was associated with more than a 20% increased

95
00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:48.460
risk of cancer-related mortality in patients with breast

96
00:05:48.560 --> 00:05:49.920
cancer.

97
00:05:51.190 --> 00:05:54.850
The relationship between obesity and poor outcomes was also seen in

98
00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:58.700
colorectal cancer, fewer studies, but very similar magnitude of

99
00:05:58.760 --> 00:06:02.280
increase in risk, was also seen in pancreatic

100
00:06:02.340 --> 00:06:05.700
cancer and in prostate cancer. So across these cancers,

101
00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:09.968
obesity was linked to poor outcomes.Now, one thing about this

102
00:06:10.008 --> 00:06:13.948
analysis was that it looked at patients with both earlier stage and later stage

103
00:06:14.008 --> 00:06:17.828
disease. And the relationship between obesity and poor outcomes, I will

104
00:06:17.968 --> 00:06:21.568
say, is much less clear in the setting of advanced disease.

105
00:06:21.598 --> 00:06:25.548
And in fact, in some cancers, there has been this obesity paradox

106
00:06:25.588 --> 00:06:29.268
where people who have more adiposity do better in the

107
00:06:29.328 --> 00:06:33.198
setting of advanced disease, and some of that may be due to the fact that

108
00:06:33.208 --> 00:06:35.968
people lose weight when they're quite sick with cancer.

109
00:06:36.008 --> 00:06:39.728
Some of it may be some of this intriguing evidence that's arising about the

110
00:06:39.768 --> 00:06:42.497
interaction between obesity and immunotherapy.

111
00:06:43.208 --> 00:06:47.028
But it does make this analysis a little bit harder to untangle

112
00:06:47.068 --> 00:06:50.938
in some cancers. And so that's why it was really, I think, very,

113
00:06:51.048 --> 00:06:54.708
very important when last, about a year and a half ago, the

114
00:06:54.788 --> 00:06:58.528
Oxford Overview Group looked specifically at the relationship

115
00:06:58.548 --> 00:07:02.028
between obesity at diagnosis and recurrence

116
00:07:02.108 --> 00:07:05.898
outcomes in patients with early-stage breast cancer to really look at

117
00:07:05.928 --> 00:07:09.808
whether, giving us some more preliminary evidence, that

118
00:07:09.888 --> 00:07:13.647
if you help somebody lose weight after they'd been diagnosed with an early-stage

119
00:07:13.728 --> 00:07:17.608
malignancy, could you bend the trajectory of poor outcomes that

120
00:07:17.648 --> 00:07:21.448
is seen in that group? And so this analysis looked at more

121
00:07:21.508 --> 00:07:24.938
than 200,000 women who were taking part in clinical

122
00:07:25.048 --> 00:07:28.008
trials of chemotherapy, radiation,

123
00:07:28.768 --> 00:07:32.748
endocrine therapy. So these were all patients taking part in studies with highly

124
00:07:32.788 --> 00:07:36.748
adjudicated cancer outcomes. A hundred and forty-seven different trials

125
00:07:36.788 --> 00:07:40.638
were part of this analysis. And what the group found was that

126
00:07:40.688 --> 00:07:44.388
each of those five-kilogram-per-meter-squared increases in body mass

127
00:07:44.488 --> 00:07:47.768
index in these women was associated with a

128
00:07:48.048 --> 00:07:51.688
6% increase specifically in the risk of distant disease

129
00:07:51.788 --> 00:07:54.788
recurrence. They also found, very

130
00:07:54.848 --> 00:07:58.508
interestingly, that this relationship was actually stronger in

131
00:07:58.568 --> 00:08:02.048
younger women than older women. So this is very different than the

132
00:08:02.068 --> 00:08:05.648
relationship between obesity and primary cancer risk.

133
00:08:05.688 --> 00:08:09.228
In this analysis, although this increased risk of

134
00:08:09.348 --> 00:08:12.708
specifically distant recurrence was seen in both younger and older

135
00:08:12.728 --> 00:08:16.228
women and women with higher stage and lower stage disease,

136
00:08:16.888 --> 00:08:20.668
where this absolute increase in risk was highest was younger

137
00:08:20.768 --> 00:08:23.028
women with node-positive cancers.

138
00:08:23.208 --> 00:08:27.128
So we don't really understand why the biology is so different when you're

139
00:08:27.138 --> 00:08:31.068
looking at primary risk versus prognosis in early-stage

140
00:08:31.088 --> 00:08:34.889
disease. But this has been seen not only in this analysis but also

141
00:08:34.968 --> 00:08:38.728
others, very strong relationship between obesity and poor

142
00:08:38.788 --> 00:08:41.369
outcomes in younger women with breast cancer.

143
00:08:42.889 --> 00:08:46.408
The analysis went on to look at patients receiving different types of

144
00:08:46.428 --> 00:08:49.528
therapy to see if perhaps the adverse effect of

145
00:08:49.588 --> 00:08:53.528
obesity was related to endocrine signaling or if they

146
00:08:53.568 --> 00:08:57.328
could try to untangle that. And they found, in fact, that poor outcomes were seen

147
00:08:57.368 --> 00:09:01.088
across the board for patients who were treated with chemotherapy alone,

148
00:09:01.468 --> 00:09:03.698
with endocrine therapy, or the combination.

149
00:09:04.568 --> 00:09:08.468
And they also demonstrated that this relationship between obesity and poor outcomes

150
00:09:08.548 --> 00:09:11.688
was seen in both hormone receptor-positive and hormone

151
00:09:11.748 --> 00:09:15.098
receptor-negative cancer. So really, a very, very

152
00:09:15.128 --> 00:09:19.048
broad spectrum of patients who are potentially at risk

153
00:09:19.108 --> 00:09:22.558
of poor outcomes related to excess adiposity and

154
00:09:22.608 --> 00:09:23.218
obesity.

155
00:09:24.288 --> 00:09:27.968
So this really leads us to the central question that we hope to address today

156
00:09:27.988 --> 00:09:31.848
through these three talks. Is obesity a modifiable risk

157
00:09:31.928 --> 00:09:33.017
factor for cancer?

158
00:09:33.908 --> 00:09:37.788
Unfortunately, we don't have much evidence at this point from well-designed

159
00:09:37.828 --> 00:09:41.648
randomized trials looking at the impact of an intentional weight loss

160
00:09:41.708 --> 00:09:45.358
intervention, whether that be lifestyle, drugs, or surgery

161
00:09:45.928 --> 00:09:48.498
on the risk of developing or dying from cancer.

162
00:09:49.268 --> 00:09:52.908
But there's some really intriguing evidence that has come from long-term

163
00:09:53.048 --> 00:09:56.848
follow-up of bariatric surgery cohorts that suggest, in

164
00:09:56.988 --> 00:10:00.948
fact, that if you help someone lose weight, you can actually reduce their risk

165
00:10:00.988 --> 00:10:02.188
of developing cancer.

166
00:10:03.008 --> 00:10:06.208
It's important to recognize that these are not randomized trials.

167
00:10:06.268 --> 00:10:09.908
These are largely prospective cohorts where individuals who undergo

168
00:10:10.008 --> 00:10:13.728
bariatric surgery are matched by age, BMI,

169
00:10:13.808 --> 00:10:17.588
gender, and often comorbidity status with individuals who

170
00:10:17.628 --> 00:10:21.368
don't undergo bariatric surgery, and then the two cohorts are followed

171
00:10:21.428 --> 00:10:25.248
over time. This recent meta-analysis looked at 32

172
00:10:25.367 --> 00:10:28.648
different cohort studies of bariatric surgery with matched

173
00:10:28.728 --> 00:10:32.608
controls, more than 500,000 patients who underwent

174
00:10:32.648 --> 00:10:35.808
surgery with 1.8 million matched controls.

175
00:10:36.268 --> 00:10:40.168
Over the follow-up period, which did vary from study to study, there were

176
00:10:40.208 --> 00:10:43.948
more than 95,000 total cancers diagnosed, and

177
00:10:44.428 --> 00:10:48.348
41,000 of these were what we think of as obesity-related cancers.

178
00:10:49.068 --> 00:10:52.448
You can see when looking at the relationship between bariatric

179
00:10:52.488 --> 00:10:56.348
surgery and overall cancer risk that the individuals who

180
00:10:56.408 --> 00:10:59.908
underwent bariatric surgery were at almost 40%

181
00:11:00.028 --> 00:11:03.568
lower risk of developing any malignancy in the

182
00:11:03.608 --> 00:11:07.328
follow-up period as compared to individuals who did not undergo

183
00:11:07.408 --> 00:11:10.808
bariatric surgery. And although the numbers are a little bit

184
00:11:10.948 --> 00:11:14.728
smaller when looking at obesity-related cancer, the

185
00:11:14.768 --> 00:11:18.308
effect was actually even a little bit stronger, that individuals who

186
00:11:18.368 --> 00:11:22.158
underwent bariatric surgery were at lower risk of developing

187
00:11:22.188 --> 00:11:23.128
malignancy.

188
00:11:24.468 --> 00:11:28.288
Now, as some of these cohorts have matured, we've been able to look not

189
00:11:28.348 --> 00:11:32.338
only at overall cancer risk but also specifically at some of

190
00:11:32.368 --> 00:11:35.768
the cancers which are most strongly related to obesity.

191
00:11:36.368 --> 00:11:39.868
So this systematic review of intentional weight loss and cancer risk

192
00:11:39.908 --> 00:11:43.708
included 18 studies, including primarily bariatric

193
00:11:43.788 --> 00:11:46.828
surgery studies, but one lifestyle-based weight loss trial.

194
00:11:47.408 --> 00:11:51.318
They demonstrated, first, a reduction in overall risk of malignancy

195
00:11:51.428 --> 00:11:54.188
and, in particular, of obesity-related cancers.

196
00:11:54.588 --> 00:11:58.428
But what I think is most interesting about this review was they were able to

197
00:11:58.488 --> 00:12:02.478
look at the relationship between the development of

198
00:12:02.588 --> 00:12:06.488
specific cancers and whether or not patients had taken part in

199
00:12:06.588 --> 00:12:09.228
a weight loss intervention, largely surgery.

200
00:12:09.748 --> 00:12:13.348
They found that some of the cancers most tightly related to

201
00:12:13.428 --> 00:12:15.548
obesity were not surprisingly,

202
00:12:16.148 --> 00:12:19.628
significantly reduced in risk in people who underwent

203
00:12:19.668 --> 00:12:23.248
bariatric surgery. An up to 50% lower risk of breast

204
00:12:23.348 --> 00:12:26.748
cancer, up to 60% lower risk of colorectal

205
00:12:26.788 --> 00:12:30.708
cancer, a reduction in the risk of pancreatic cancer, which is quite

206
00:12:30.748 --> 00:12:34.658
notable given our limited treatment strategies for this malignancy.

207
00:12:34.688 --> 00:12:38.588
Endometrial cancer also significantly less likely in patients

208
00:12:38.608 --> 00:12:42.548
who underwent bariatric surgery, and emerging evidence in many of

209
00:12:42.588 --> 00:12:44.108
the other obesity-related

210
00:12:44.188 --> 00:12:48.224
malignancies.Looking

211
00:12:48.284 --> 00:12:52.104
into the bariatric surgery a little further, the picture becomes a little

212
00:12:52.124 --> 00:12:55.754
bit more complex. And one of the studies that has contributed

213
00:12:55.764 --> 00:12:59.704
probably the most to our understanding of obesity and cancer over

214
00:12:59.744 --> 00:13:03.484
time has been, I'm sorry, of bariatric surgery and cancer

215
00:13:03.544 --> 00:13:07.124
risk over time, has been the Swedish Obese Subjects study.

216
00:13:07.144 --> 00:13:11.124
This study, although relatively modest in size, 2,000 patients who

217
00:13:11.184 --> 00:13:15.004
underwent surgery matched with about 2,000 matched controls, the

218
00:13:15.044 --> 00:13:18.564
follow-up time from this cohort is now more than 25

219
00:13:18.604 --> 00:13:22.484
years in the bariatric surgery population and almost that in the

220
00:13:22.504 --> 00:13:26.434
control group. And what they found interestingly is that

221
00:13:26.464 --> 00:13:30.364
this relationship between bariatric surgery and subsequent cancer

222
00:13:30.404 --> 00:13:33.764
risk, at least in this cohort, really seems to be seen

223
00:13:33.824 --> 00:13:37.424
primarily amongst women as opposed to men.

224
00:13:37.534 --> 00:13:40.664
This has been shown in some other cohorts as well, but

225
00:13:40.704 --> 00:13:44.464
suggesting that this relationship does seem to

226
00:13:44.484 --> 00:13:46.204
be somewhat gender dependent.

227
00:13:47.053 --> 00:13:50.844
The other very interesting finding from this cohort has been

228
00:13:50.904 --> 00:13:54.544
looking a little bit at metabolic dysfunction in

229
00:13:54.624 --> 00:13:56.564
cancer risk, because we know that obesity,

230
00:13:57.364 --> 00:14:00.754
BMI, is an imperfect marker of metabolic health.

231
00:14:01.164 --> 00:14:05.084
And so another analysis from the Swedish Obesity study

232
00:14:05.164 --> 00:14:08.784
has looked at the relationship between fasting insulin level

233
00:14:09.304 --> 00:14:13.224
and this connection between bariatric surgery and

234
00:14:13.324 --> 00:14:16.884
subsequent cancer risk. And what it shows is that patients who

235
00:14:16.984 --> 00:14:19.564
have normal insulin resistance

236
00:14:20.844 --> 00:14:24.724
at baseline do not seem to have the same difference in

237
00:14:24.864 --> 00:14:28.164
risk of malignancy by bariatric surgery.

238
00:14:28.264 --> 00:14:31.984
So as insulin resistance mounts, these two curves separating,

239
00:14:32.104 --> 00:14:35.844
suggesting a larger potential benefit of bariatric

240
00:14:35.944 --> 00:14:39.924
surgery in reducing subsequent cancer risk, which I think will be quite

241
00:14:39.964 --> 00:14:43.864
interesting when we look later at some of the mechanisms of GLP-1s and

242
00:14:43.924 --> 00:14:46.344
how they may impact long-term cancer risk.

243
00:14:47.504 --> 00:14:51.344
So we've talked a lot about bariatric surgery, but recognizing that really

244
00:14:51.404 --> 00:14:54.904
only a small number of people with obesity undergo

245
00:14:54.964 --> 00:14:58.844
bariatric surgery. What do we know about other types of

246
00:14:59.024 --> 00:15:02.764
weight loss? I'm going to specifically focus a little bit on

247
00:15:02.844 --> 00:15:06.594
lifestyle-based weight loss, which we know generates a much smaller

248
00:15:06.684 --> 00:15:10.664
degree of weight loss than either surgery or medication.

249
00:15:11.004 --> 00:15:14.544
But there is some evidence that lifestyle-based weight loss could

250
00:15:14.624 --> 00:15:17.604
impact an individual's risk of developing malignancy.

251
00:15:17.724 --> 00:15:21.104
So this was an analysis from a pooling

252
00:15:21.204 --> 00:15:25.104
project looking at studies of diet and in cancer that included more

253
00:15:25.144 --> 00:15:28.014
than 180,000 post-menopausal women.

254
00:15:28.544 --> 00:15:32.424
And they looked at the relationship between weight change over a 10-year

255
00:15:32.464 --> 00:15:36.314
period and breast cancer risk. There were three measurements that were

256
00:15:36.364 --> 00:15:38.434
taken of weight in this population.

257
00:15:38.464 --> 00:15:42.224
Patients were considered having stable weight loss if they lost

258
00:15:42.284 --> 00:15:45.744
weight during the first five-year period, and then they kept that off during the

259
00:15:45.784 --> 00:15:49.564
second-year period. Conversely, if they gained weight in the first five

260
00:15:49.604 --> 00:15:53.254
years and kept it and continued to gain weight, they were considered having weight

261
00:15:53.364 --> 00:15:56.684
gain. There were almost 7,000 cancer cases that were

262
00:15:56.704 --> 00:15:59.344
diagnosed over an eight-year period.

263
00:15:59.864 --> 00:16:03.674
And what they found was that sustained weight loss achieved through

264
00:16:03.744 --> 00:16:07.224
lifestyle means was associated with a lower risk of

265
00:16:07.244 --> 00:16:10.974
developing breast cancer. And you can see here that this is a fairly linear

266
00:16:10.974 --> 00:16:14.664
relationship. The individuals who successfully maintained weight

267
00:16:14.724 --> 00:16:18.564
loss more than nine kilograms had about a 40% lower

268
00:16:18.644 --> 00:16:20.224
risk of developing breast cancer.

269
00:16:20.304 --> 00:16:24.224
So somewhat akin to what we've seen in some of the bariatric surgery studies.

270
00:16:24.644 --> 00:16:28.604
As the weight loss was less pronounced, the reduction was also less

271
00:16:28.624 --> 00:16:32.584
pronounced, but suggesting that perhaps this degree of weight loss

272
00:16:32.644 --> 00:16:36.164
achieved through lifestyle could also have an impact on cancer risk.

273
00:16:37.144 --> 00:16:41.084
There is one randomized study that also presents some tantalizing

274
00:16:41.204 --> 00:16:45.124
data suggesting that a lifestyle-based weight loss program could reduce

275
00:16:45.134 --> 00:16:49.104
the risk of developing cancer. This was not a study that

276
00:16:49.124 --> 00:16:51.064
was designed to answer this question.

277
00:16:51.124 --> 00:16:55.044
The Look AHEAD Study was actually a trial that enrolled individuals with

278
00:16:55.104 --> 00:16:59.064
diabetes and looked at whether a structured lifestyle intervention

279
00:16:59.104 --> 00:17:02.444
focused on weight loss could actually reduce the risk of cardiovascular

280
00:17:02.484 --> 00:17:06.325
events in this population of individuals with type 2

281
00:17:06.363 --> 00:17:10.144
diabetes. But cancer was a predefined secondary outcome,

282
00:17:10.404 --> 00:17:14.104
and the intervention in this study was very effective at

283
00:17:14.184 --> 00:17:18.035
inducing long-term weight loss. And you can see here that there was

284
00:17:18.035 --> 00:17:21.944
significant weight loss of almost 10% over the first year.

285
00:17:21.964 --> 00:17:25.815
And although that attenuated to more of a 4% to 6% weight loss over

286
00:17:25.844 --> 00:17:29.804
time, it was sustained in the population of patients

287
00:17:29.844 --> 00:17:31.664
randomized to the weight loss program.

288
00:17:32.624 --> 00:17:36.294
And what they found after 11 years of median follow-up in almost

289
00:17:36.564 --> 00:17:40.144
700 incident cancers was that there was no reduction in

290
00:17:40.244 --> 00:17:43.744
overall cancer incidence, so very different than the bariatric surgery

291
00:17:43.824 --> 00:17:47.184
literature, but about a 20% reduction in

292
00:17:47.244 --> 00:17:50.784
obesity-related cancers. And whether that was statistically significant

293
00:17:51.184 --> 00:17:54.704
or not depended on which list of obesity-related cancers that you

294
00:17:54.764 --> 00:17:58.584
used. But I think some interesting preliminary evidence that this

295
00:17:58.604 --> 00:18:02.344
degree of weight loss could have an impact on the risk of developing

296
00:18:02.424 --> 00:18:06.184
cancer, perhaps not to the degree of the 40% weight

297
00:18:06.234 --> 00:18:10.134
loss that's seen with bariatric surgery, but still a potentially meaningful

298
00:18:10.164 --> 00:18:14.124
reduction in the risk of cancer. The study also looked in a very

299
00:18:14.144 --> 00:18:16.624
exploratory way at individual malignancies.

300
00:18:16.664 --> 00:18:20.264
Again, this was only 5,000 patients, but saw a trend toward a

301
00:18:20.284 --> 00:18:24.084
reduction in pancreatic cancer and in post-menopausal breast

302
00:18:24.184 --> 00:18:27.524
cancer. So a lot more to learn, but I think that we do

303
00:18:27.604 --> 00:18:31.504
have some really interesting preliminary evidence suggesting that weight is

304
00:18:31.544 --> 00:18:34.974
indeed a factor that we can modify and potentially

305
00:18:35.024 --> 00:18:37.964
influence an individual's risk of developing cancer.

306
00:18:39.184 --> 00:18:40.804
But what about cancer recurrence?

307
00:18:40.904 --> 00:18:44.714
We have so much evidence, especially in breast cancer, that higher

308
00:18:44.804 --> 00:18:48.364
levels of adiposity at diagnosis are linked to poor outcomes.

309
00:18:48.964 --> 00:18:52.884
This is what led us to develop now, a decade ago, a phase three

310
00:18:53.024 --> 00:18:55.264
trial that will evaluate whether

311
00:18:55.364 --> 00:18:59.324
aSupervised, structured weight loss intervention

312
00:18:59.724 --> 00:19:03.544
could reduce the risk of recurrence and improve survival in patients with

313
00:19:03.624 --> 00:19:07.284
early breast cancer. The Breast Cancer Weight Loss Trial enrolled

314
00:19:07.324 --> 00:19:10.164
3,180 women between

315
00:19:10.424 --> 00:19:14.204
2016 and 2021 from more than 600

316
00:19:14.264 --> 00:19:16.544
clinics across the United States and Canada.

317
00:19:17.114 --> 00:19:20.984
Patients were eligible if they had been diagnosed with a Stage 2 to 3 breast

318
00:19:21.024 --> 00:19:24.564
cancer and had a body mass index of at least 27

319
00:19:24.604 --> 00:19:28.464
kilograms per meter squared. The patients were randomized one to

320
00:19:28.543 --> 00:19:32.364
one to a two-year telephone-based weight loss program that was a

321
00:19:32.404 --> 00:19:36.044
lifestyle program focused on caloric restriction and increased

322
00:19:36.104 --> 00:19:39.794
physical activity, or to a health education control group.

323
00:19:40.324 --> 00:19:43.873
Our primary outcome of this study looks at invasive disease-free

324
00:19:43.964 --> 00:19:47.924
survival, and we are hoping to have these results within the next one

325
00:19:47.964 --> 00:19:51.833
to two years. But in the meantime, have started to analyze a number of

326
00:19:51.864 --> 00:19:55.693
our key secondary outcomes. The first of these was

327
00:19:55.724 --> 00:19:59.513
published this year, and I'm going to just spend a second

328
00:19:59.564 --> 00:20:02.024
talking about who these patients were.

329
00:20:02.084 --> 00:20:03.564
So you can see, on average,

330
00:20:04.624 --> 00:20:08.334
the average age at diagnosis and participation in this trial was

331
00:20:08.544 --> 00:20:09.034
53.

332
00:20:09.864 --> 00:20:13.564
At baseline, the average BMI was 34 kilograms per meter squared.

333
00:20:13.624 --> 00:20:17.384
So patients were largely well into the range of obesity

334
00:20:17.444 --> 00:20:19.184
during participation in this trial.

335
00:20:19.924 --> 00:20:23.564
About 80% of patients were White, about 13% African

336
00:20:23.604 --> 00:20:27.304
American, and about 7.5% of patients were Hispanic.

337
00:20:27.724 --> 00:20:31.544
On average, there were 10 months between initial diagnosis and enrollment in

338
00:20:31.604 --> 00:20:32.164
this study.

339
00:20:33.124 --> 00:20:36.904
So the first secondary outcome that we've looked at is, was the

340
00:20:36.924 --> 00:20:39.244
intervention successful in inducing weight loss?

341
00:20:39.344 --> 00:20:41.124
You can't really study whether a

342
00:20:42.184 --> 00:20:46.034
weight loss program improves outcomes if it doesn't actually impact patients'

343
00:20:46.124 --> 00:20:49.604
weight. And so we published in JAMA Oncology last year that the

344
00:20:49.644 --> 00:20:53.304
intervention group versus controls lost almost 6% of

345
00:20:53.344 --> 00:20:57.214
baseline body weight at one year. We also demonstrated that

346
00:20:57.244 --> 00:21:01.104
the proportion of patients who lost 5 and 10% of baseline

347
00:21:01.124 --> 00:21:04.934
body weight was significantly greater in our intervention group, with almost

348
00:21:05.124 --> 00:21:09.084
50% of patients losing at least 5% of baseline weight

349
00:21:09.104 --> 00:21:12.654
and more than 20% losing more than 10% of baseline

350
00:21:12.744 --> 00:21:16.054
weight. And that was compared to 12% and only

351
00:21:16.184 --> 00:21:19.624
6% of control patients who met these weight loss goals.

352
00:21:21.144 --> 00:21:25.084
We also have looked at some of the correlative science,

353
00:21:25.284 --> 00:21:29.024
looking at the impact of the weight loss intervention on key

354
00:21:29.064 --> 00:21:31.654
metabolic and inflammatory biomarkers.

355
00:21:32.304 --> 00:21:35.624
These data were presented at the San Antonio Breast Cancer

356
00:21:35.704 --> 00:21:39.604
Symposium and demonstrate that this degree

357
00:21:39.664 --> 00:21:43.564
of weight loss that we saw in our intervention had a significant

358
00:21:43.684 --> 00:21:46.784
impact on metabolic and inflammatory biomarkers.

359
00:21:47.284 --> 00:21:51.144
We saw about a 21% reduction in fasting insulin at

360
00:21:51.204 --> 00:21:54.554
six months that was largely maintained at 24 months.

361
00:21:55.324 --> 00:21:58.304
We also looked at insulin resistance measured by HOMA.

362
00:21:58.364 --> 00:22:02.214
And I just want to point out that at baseline, you see that both groups had a HOMA

363
00:22:02.284 --> 00:22:06.204
score of more than four, which demonstrates a fairly high level of

364
00:22:06.224 --> 00:22:09.934
baseline insulin resistance. We decreased this by

365
00:22:10.164 --> 00:22:13.954
25% in the intervention versus control group at six months,

366
00:22:14.364 --> 00:22:18.224
and although there was some attenuation of this at 24 months, still saw

367
00:22:18.234 --> 00:22:22.174
a significant reduction in insulin resistance in patients randomized

368
00:22:22.244 --> 00:22:26.064
to our weight loss intervention. We also looked at fasting

369
00:22:26.124 --> 00:22:29.764
leptin and saw very similar reductions at

370
00:22:29.844 --> 00:22:33.004
six and 24 months. And finally, we looked at

371
00:22:33.064 --> 00:22:36.353
C-reactive protein as a general marker of inflammation.

372
00:22:36.814 --> 00:22:40.284
And although the reductions were not numerically as large, we did see

373
00:22:40.464 --> 00:22:44.284
significant reduction in our intervention group versus controls, which

374
00:22:44.344 --> 00:22:48.244
interestingly, unlike the metabolic markers, became a bit more

375
00:22:48.284 --> 00:22:52.204
significant over time as the intervention progressed further.

376
00:22:52.244 --> 00:22:56.064
We will continue to follow these patients and again, hope to have more information

377
00:22:56.104 --> 00:23:00.084
about the impact of this structured weight loss program on outcomes in early

378
00:23:00.104 --> 00:23:03.584
breast cancer within the next year or so.

379
00:23:03.644 --> 00:23:07.524
So in conclusion, I'm hopeful that this sets us up well for the rest

380
00:23:07.624 --> 00:23:09.944
of our session focusing on GLP-1s.

381
00:23:11.124 --> 00:23:15.044
We know that obesity is related to both an increased risk of

382
00:23:15.064 --> 00:23:16.884
developing and dying from cancer.

383
00:23:17.404 --> 00:23:21.184
Our preliminary evidence suggests that this is a modifiable risk factor.

384
00:23:21.304 --> 00:23:25.184
If we can find a way to help patients lose weight and sustain weight loss,

385
00:23:25.624 --> 00:23:29.184
we do definitely have the possibility of impacting their risk of

386
00:23:29.204 --> 00:23:32.974
developing malignancy and the likelihood that they'll survive if they're

387
00:23:32.984 --> 00:23:36.444
diagnosed with an early-stage cancer in particular.

388
00:23:36.534 --> 00:23:38.164
Thank you so much for your attention.

389
00:23:39.984 --> 00:23:43.724
I think we can take one or two questions if you have a direct question

390
00:23:43.844 --> 00:23:45.584
about the presentation.

391
00:23:46.844 --> 00:23:50.724
We do have 20 minutes at the end kind of reserved for a panel discussion,

392
00:23:50.824 --> 00:23:52.624
but if you have an immediate question, please.

393
00:23:53.764 --> 00:23:56.744
Thank you. Nice talk. Question about visceral obesity

394
00:23:57.564 --> 00:23:57.904
and

395
00:23:58.744 --> 00:24:01.504
the inflammation that people speculate is involved.

396
00:24:02.264 --> 00:24:05.504
There is the thin patient who has visceral obesity,

397
00:24:06.284 --> 00:24:07.844
and do you think we should be

398
00:24:08.744 --> 00:24:12.244
switching to body composition assessments rather than just BMI?

399
00:24:13.124 --> 00:24:14.564
I think that's an excellent question.

400
00:24:14.604 --> 00:24:15.204
And actually,

401
00:24:16.104 --> 00:24:19.824
as Steve may remember, with that International Agency for Research in Cancer

402
00:24:20.604 --> 00:24:24.544
monograph that we put together, there was a day-long argument about what's

403
00:24:24.584 --> 00:24:28.384
the right measure. I think we all recognize that body mass index

404
00:24:28.464 --> 00:24:32.424
is easy and cheap, but it is not a very accurate

405
00:24:32.484 --> 00:24:36.384
measure of metabolic health. I think it was really interesting to look

406
00:24:36.424 --> 00:24:40.324
at the data from that Swedish obesity study showing that people who

407
00:24:40.384 --> 00:24:42.664
have bariatric surgery generally are in--

408
00:24:43.744 --> 00:24:47.704
you need to have a BMI of at least 30, but most of the time, the average BMI for

409
00:24:47.764 --> 00:24:51.384
that procedure is in the 40s, and yet patients who

410
00:24:51.444 --> 00:24:55.343
underwent bariatric surgery, even with those high BMIs, did not all have insulin

411
00:24:55.384 --> 00:24:58.924
resistance. And in that study, there wasn't a benefit

412
00:24:59.424 --> 00:25:03.404
of bariatric surgery in terms of cancer risk for patients who did not

413
00:25:03.464 --> 00:25:06.984
have metabolic dysfunction. So I think your question is a great

414
00:25:07.084 --> 00:25:11.044
one. I think what's hard is that the evidence that we have so far largely

415
00:25:11.084 --> 00:25:15.044
comes from these large cohorts and these databases, and BMI

416
00:25:15.084 --> 00:25:17.664
is easily available, but body composition is not.

417
00:25:17.774 --> 00:25:21.164
And I do think that there is a lot that we lose by just

418
00:25:21.224 --> 00:25:25.024
focusing on body mass index. And hopefully, as we move

419
00:25:25.064 --> 00:25:28.484
forward, and especially thinking about what patients might actually benefit from

420
00:25:28.524 --> 00:25:32.444
these types of prevention strategies, we're going to need to use something a

421
00:25:32.484 --> 00:25:34.404
lot more precise than body mass index.

422
00:25:35.268 --> 00:25:39.188
Most of the postmenopausal breast cancer patients are getting DEXA scans,

423
00:25:40.148 --> 00:25:44.028
and it's the same machine can give the same information.

424
00:25:44.048 --> 00:25:44.538
We just don't

425
00:25:45.448 --> 00:25:46.468
do it in the clinics.

426
00:25:47.228 --> 00:25:50.928
Right. You need kind of a different algorithm and program, and unfortunately, a lot

427
00:25:50.948 --> 00:25:53.788
of clinics-- We went through this with the breast cancer weight loss study.

428
00:25:53.848 --> 00:25:57.708
We really wanted to be able to look at body composition, and we

429
00:25:57.748 --> 00:26:01.668
found that especially, many of the patients are treated in community

430
00:26:01.768 --> 00:26:02.468
centers and they

431
00:26:03.668 --> 00:26:06.168
don't have the ability. Even though it's the same machine, they don't have the

432
00:26:06.208 --> 00:26:09.248
software, they don't have anyone to interpret it. But I agree.

433
00:26:09.728 --> 00:26:13.288
Now there's much better data that comes from some of these

434
00:26:13.968 --> 00:26:17.948
scales and things that used to be very poor quality

435
00:26:18.028 --> 00:26:21.868
data, but there's been huge advances in the use of these

436
00:26:21.908 --> 00:26:25.428
bioimpedance monitors that you find all over the place.

437
00:26:25.488 --> 00:26:29.188
So I think that we are at a time when there is a lot more opportunity there, for

438
00:26:29.288 --> 00:26:29.588
sure.

439
00:26:31.548 --> 00:26:34.648
Maybe one more question, and then we can conclude.

440
00:26:36.328 --> 00:26:40.088
Hi, very nice presentation. So my question is, I

441
00:26:40.168 --> 00:26:42.588
was wondering, people with normal BMI,

442
00:26:44.008 --> 00:26:46.268
how does that apply? So

443
00:26:47.288 --> 00:26:51.248
weight loss in normal BMI will not have any

444
00:26:51.348 --> 00:26:52.628
effect on cancer risk?

445
00:26:53.568 --> 00:26:55.188
So that is a great question.

446
00:26:56.048 --> 00:27:00.008
There are some studies that have suggested that people that are metabolically

447
00:27:00.068 --> 00:27:04.008
unhealthy, even if they do have a normal body mass index, may

448
00:27:04.088 --> 00:27:08.018
be at increased risk of developing malignancy, but there's a lot more that

449
00:27:08.048 --> 00:27:11.888
we don't know. I do think that we need to think a little

450
00:27:11.908 --> 00:27:13.658
bit about this

451
00:27:14.648 --> 00:27:17.288
metabolic health and obesity and cancer risk.

452
00:27:17.298 --> 00:27:20.838
There was a lot of excitement, for example, about the use of

453
00:27:20.868 --> 00:27:24.618
metformin to potentially improve cancer outcomes,

454
00:27:24.748 --> 00:27:28.688
and when you look at observational studies of individuals who were taking

455
00:27:28.748 --> 00:27:32.588
metformin for diabetes, or it's not used as widely, but

456
00:27:32.628 --> 00:27:36.328
sometimes for weight loss, there seemed to be this really strong signal

457
00:27:36.808 --> 00:27:40.268
that that medication was linked to a lower risk of

458
00:27:40.288 --> 00:27:43.768
developing breast cancer in particular, linked to better cancer outcomes.

459
00:27:44.188 --> 00:27:47.808
But when this was studied in a phase three trial and the drug was given to normal

460
00:27:47.888 --> 00:27:51.857
weight patients without any kind of metabolic dysfunction, the

461
00:27:51.908 --> 00:27:55.688
drug did not have any beneficial effect at all in lowering cancer risk.

462
00:27:55.838 --> 00:27:59.438
So I think we need to be careful and figure out when we think about

463
00:27:59.468 --> 00:28:02.948
metabolic health, what are we really measuring and who are the

464
00:28:02.968 --> 00:28:06.868
people that potentially might benefit that don't have outward

465
00:28:06.888 --> 00:28:10.577
signs of obesity? I think that it would probably not be the best

466
00:28:10.648 --> 00:28:12.678
strategy to be using some of these

467
00:28:13.728 --> 00:28:17.448
medications for diabetes or weight loss in an unselected group of

468
00:28:17.488 --> 00:28:19.328
patients with normal body mass index.

469
00:28:19.408 --> 00:28:23.028
But we do need to figure out what are those metabolic markers that put normal

470
00:28:23.088 --> 00:28:26.798
weight people at higher risk of these kind of obesity-related

471
00:28:26.888 --> 00:28:27.408
cancers.

472
00:28:28.768 --> 00:28:32.718
I'm wondering if this is related to the inflammatory cytokines,

473
00:28:33.168 --> 00:28:37.068
because some people with normal BMI can have insulin resistance

474
00:28:37.188 --> 00:28:37.748
too, right?

475
00:28:37.988 --> 00:28:41.788
Exactly. I think that this is kind of an area of really

476
00:28:41.888 --> 00:28:45.878
active research. Inflammation, certainly there are people that have kind of

477
00:28:45.928 --> 00:28:49.618
the immune suppressive patterns that we see in individuals with obesity that are

478
00:28:49.628 --> 00:28:52.718
normal weight, and we don't understand exactly why that is.

479
00:28:52.718 --> 00:28:56.357
I think that there is this really important, and I know that

480
00:28:57.028 --> 00:29:00.938
Dr. Hustings is going to talk about this too, but this interplay between

481
00:29:00.968 --> 00:29:04.508
inflammation and metabolism and the immune system that is

482
00:29:04.568 --> 00:29:08.438
impacted by obesity, but other things as well, and we need to kind of untangle that

483
00:29:08.488 --> 00:29:12.108
as we think about which patients may be the best potential subjects

484
00:29:12.148 --> 00:29:14.008
for these types of studies.

485
00:29:15.368 --> 00:29:15.608
Great.

486
00:29:15.988 --> 00:29:16.268
Thank you.

487
00:29:16.288 --> 00:29:16.808
Thanks, Jennifer.

488
00:29:17.108 --> 00:29:17.408
Thanks.

489
00:29:17.588 --> 00:29:19.328
So, the next speaker will be

490
00:29:20.168 --> 00:29:23.328
Dr. Steve Hustings, and he's going to actually present some of the

491
00:29:23.408 --> 00:29:26.188
preclinical and mechanism data.

